Relationship between eigen decomposition and SVD

The columns of \boldsymbol {V} are eigenvectors of \boldsymbol {A}^T\boldsymbol {A}

The columns of \boldsymbol {U} are eigenvectors of \boldsymbol {A}\boldsymbol {A}^T

{{\sigma _{i}({\mathbf {A}})}}={\sqrt {\lambda _{i}({{{\mathbf {A}}{\mathbf {A}}^{\mathsf {T}}}})}}={\sqrt {\lambda _{i}({\mathbf {A}}^{\mathsf {T}}{\mathbf {A}})}}

Let \mathbf {A}\in \mathbb {R}^{m\times  n}. If \left |\left |\cdot \right |\right |_{a} and \left |\left |\cdot \right |\right |_{b} are norms on \mathbb {R}^{n} and \mathbb {R}^{m}, we have \left |\left |\mathbf {A}\right |\right |_{a\to  b}\ :=\ \sup _{\left |\left |\mathbf {x}\right |\right |_{a}\leq  1}\left |\left |\mathbf {A}\mathbf {x}\right |\right |_{b}.
It satisfies the three criteria for norm, and is submultiplicative ||\boldsymbol {A}\boldsymbol {B}||_{a\to  b}\ \leq \ ||\boldsymbol {A}||_{a\to  b}\cdot  ||\boldsymbol {B}||_{a\to  b};. 
||{\cal  A}||_{2\to 2}\;=\;\sigma _{1}({\cal  A})\;\;(\mathrm {{spectral\ norm}},\;\mathrm {{write\ as}}\;||{\cal  A}||\;\;);\;
\begin {array}{l}{{||{\boldsymbol {A}}||_{1\to  b}\ =\ \operatorname *{max}_{j=1,\cdots ,n}||{\boldsymbol {A e}}_{j}||_{b}}}\\ {{||{\boldsymbol {A}}||_{a\to \infty }\ =\ \operatorname *{max}_{i=1,\cdots ,m}||{\boldsymbol {e}}_{i}^{*}{\boldsymbol {A}}||_{b}^{*}\,,\ \ ||{\boldsymbol {v}}||_{b}^{*}\ :=\ \operatorname *{sup}_{||{\boldsymbol {u}}||_{b}\leq 1}\langle {\boldsymbol {u}},{\boldsymbol {v}}\rangle \,,}}\end {array}

Eg.

Spectral norm ||A||_{2 \to  2}=\sigma _{1}(A)=||\sigma (A)||_{\infty }

Frobenius norm \left ||\mathbf {A}\right ||_{F}\ =\ \sqrt {\sum _{i=1}^{\min \{m,n\}}\sigma _{i}^{2}(\mathbf {A})}\ =\ \left ||\mathbf {\sigma }(\mathbf {A})\right ||_{2}

Suppose that
f:\mathcal {X}\mapsto \mathcal {Y} with \mathcal {X} and \mathcal {Y} being open sets;
||\cdot ||_{\mathcal {X}} and ||\cdot ||_{\mathcal {Y}} are norms on \mathcal {X} and \mathcal {Y}, respectively. f(\cdot ) is Lipschitz continuous over \mathcal {X} if \exists L<\infty \,, such that ||f(\boldsymbol {y})-f(\boldsymbol {x})||_{\mathcal {Y}}\ \leq \ L(\boldsymbol {x})\,||\boldsymbol {y}-\boldsymbol {x}||_{\mathcal {X}}\,,\quad \forall \boldsymbol {x},\ \boldsymbol {y}\in \mathcal {X}.

Let f:\mathbb {R}^{n}\mapsto \mathbb {R} be twice continuously differentiable. For any fixed \mathbf {x} and \mathbf {y}, we have 
abla f(\mathbf {y})\;=\;
abla f(\mathbf {x})\,+\,\int _{0}^{1}
abla ^{2}f(\mathbf {z}(t))\cdot (\mathbf {y}-\mathbf {x})dt for some \mathbf {z}(t)=(1-t)\mathbf {x}+t\mathbf {y} with t\in (0,1)\,, and that  oxed {f(\mathbf {y})\;=\;f(\mathbf {x})+(
