fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let X be a random variable. Then the following are equivalent.

X is sub-Gaussian;

\exists  a > 0 such that \mathbb {E}(\exp (aX^2)) < \infty ;

\exists  \ell , \forall  \lambda  > 0, \mathbb {E}(\exp (\lambda  X)) \leq  X \exp (\lambda ^2 \ell );

\exists  K' > 0 \forall  p > 1 (\mathbb {E}|X|^{p})^{1/p} \leq  K' \sqrt {p}.

For p > 0, define
    \lVert  X \rVert _{\psi _p} = \inf  \left \{K > 0 \mid  \mathbb {E} \exp ^{\left (\frac {X}{k}\right )^p}\right \}
    If X is Sub-Gaussian Random Variables then this is well defined and makes our space a Banach Space.

A class of subsets \mathscr {F} of \Omega  is a \sigma -field if the following holds

\Omega  \in  \mathscr {F}

If A \in  \mathscr {F} then A^c \in  \mathscr {F}

If A_1, A_2, \ldots  \in  \mathscr {F} then \bigcup _{i = 1}^{\infty } A_i \in  \mathscr {F}

A set function is a real-valued function defined on some class of subsets of \Omega . A set function P on a field \mathscr {F} is a probability measure if it satisfies these conditions:


0\leq  P(A)\leq 1 for A\in \mathscr {F};

P(\varnothing )=0, P(\Omega )=1;

if A_{1},A_{2},\ldots  is a disjoint sequence of \mathscr {F} sets and if \bigcup _{k=1}^{\infty }A_{k}\in \mathscr {F}, then P\Big (\bigcup _{k=1}^{\infty }A_{k}\Big )=\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }P(A_{k}).

A class \mathscr {L} is a \lambda -system if it contains \Omega  and is closed under the formation of complements and of finite and countable disjoint unions:


\Omega \in \mathscr {L};


A\in \mathscr {L} implies A^{c}\in \mathscr {L};


A_{1},A_{2},\ldots ,\in \mathscr {L} and A_{n}\cap  A_{m}=\varnothing  for m\neq  n imply \bigcup _{n}A_{n}\in \mathscr {L}.

A class \mathscr {M} of subsets of \Omega  is monotone if it is closed under the formation of monotone unions and intersections:


A_{1},A_{2},\ldots \in \mathscr {M} and A_{n}\uparrow  A imply A\in \mathscr {M};

A_{1},A_{2},\ \ldots \in \mathscr {M} and A_{n}\downarrow  A imply A\in \mathscr {M}.

Let (\Omega , \mathscr {F}, P) be an arbitrary probability space, and let X be a real-valued function on \Omega . X is a simple random variable if it has finite range and if 
\left [\omega  \mid  X(\omega ) = x \right ] \in  \mathscr {F}
for each x in its finite range.

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
Consider the function 
X = \sum _{i} x_i I_{A_i}
If A_i are finite partition of \Omega  into \mathscr {F}-sets, then inverse image is at most countable union of the A_i's, which is an \mathscr {F}-set. Therefore, this function is measurable.

